[[File:Thompson Memorial Chapel - Williams College.jpg|thumb|Thompson Memorial Chapel, [[Williams College]]]] [[File:Union Theological Seminary NYC 001 002 combined.jpg|right|200px|thumb|[[Union Theological Seminary (New York)|Union Theological Seminary]] in [[New York City]]]] [[File:The Cloisters Hudson River crop.jpg|thumb|200px|[[The Cloisters]] in [[Manhattan]]]] [[File:Thompson Library (Vassar College).jpg|200px|thumb|[[Thompson Memorial Library]] at [[Vassar College]]]] [[File:Sonnenburg Mansion, Canandaigua, New York.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Sonnenberg Gardens]] in [[Canandaigua, New York]]]]
'''Allen & Collens''' was an architectural partnership between '''Francis Richmond Allen''' and '''Charles Collens''' that was active from 1904 to 1931.<ref name="nrhpinv_ny">{{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=59|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration: Canandaigua Post Office|date=December 1986|accessdate=2009-06-14 |author=Larry E. Gobrecht |publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]}} ''See also:'' {{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=65|title=Accompanying 14 photos}}</ref>{{rp|5}} Allen had previously worked in the Boston-based partnerships Allen & Kenway (1878–91) and Allen & Vance (1896-98),<ref>Marquis, ed.''Who's Who in New England'' 1915.</ref> which executed [[Lathrop House (Vassar College)|Lathrop House]] (1901) and [[Davison House]] (1902) at [[Vassar College]]. The firm was known for its [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]] design work.
Francis R. Allen died in November 1931. Charles Collens continued to practice under the name Collens, Willis and Beckonert. Collens died in September 1956.<ref>{{cite news|title=F. R. Allen Dead; Boston Architect |newspaper=New York Times|date=November 8, 1931|url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0E17F83F591B728DDDA10894D9415B818FF1D3}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Charles Collens Dies; Designed Buildings Here|newspaper=Hartford Courant|date=September 20, 1956|page= 5|url= https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courant/access/898297302.html?dids=898297302:898297302&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Sep+20%2C+1956&author=&pub=Hartford+Courant&desc=Charles+Collens+Dies%3B+Designed+Buildings+Here&pqatl=google}}</ref>
==Notable works== * [[Central Presbyterian Church (New York City)|Central Presbyterian Church]], 593 Park Avenue, [[New York City|New York, New York]] (Allen & Collens)<ref>{{cite web|title=Central Presbyterian Church |url=http://www.nycago.org/Organs/NYC/html/CentralPres.html |website=nycago.org |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151229180038/http://www.nycago.org/Organs/NYC/html/CentralPres.html |archivedate=2015-12-29 }}</ref> * [[The Cloisters]] museum buildings, [[Fort Tryon Park]], New York, New York (Allen, Collens & Willis)<ref>{{cite news|title=Cloisters Opened on Tryon Heights|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 11, 1938|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1938/05/11/archives/cloisters-opened-on-tryon-heights-rockefeller-disclaims-praise-as.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Architects File Plans For the New Cloisters|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 6, 1935|url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0915FA3458177A93C4A9178FD85F418385F9}}("Plans of the Cloisters Building ... were filed yesterday by Allen, Collens & Williams, the architects.")</ref> * [[Thompson Memorial Library]], [[Vassar College]], [[Poughkeepsie, New York]] (Allen & Collens) * [[First Parish Church (Waltham, Massachusetts)|First Parish Church]], 87 School St., [[Waltham, Massachusetts]] (Allen & Collens)<ref name=nris>{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref> * [[Hartford Seminary Foundation]], 55 Elizabeth St. and 72-120 Sherman St. [[Hartford, Connecticut]] (Collens)<ref name=nris/> * Lindsey Chapel, Emmanuel Church, Boston (Allen & Collens)<ref>{{cite web|title=Architects & Craftsmen of Lindsey Chapel, Emmanuel Church, Boston|publisher=Emmanuel Church|url=http://www.emmanuel-boston.org/LindseyChapel/LCartisans.html|access-date=2012-06-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308140051/http://www.emmanuel-boston.org/LindseyChapel/LCartisans.html|archive-date=2012-03-08|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> * [[Newton City Hall and War Memorial]], 1000 Commonwealth Ave. [[Newton, Massachusetts]] (Allen & Collens)<ref name=nris/> * [[Reformed Dutch Church of Poughkeepsie]], 70 Hooker Ave. Poughkeepsie, New York (Collens)<ref name=nris/> * The mansion at [[Sonnenberg Gardens]], the estate house of Mr. and Mrs. Frederick F. Thompson, [[Canandaigua, New York]]<ref name=nrhpinv_ny/>{{rp|5}} * Stillington Hall mansion, [[Gloucester, Massachusetts]]<ref>{{cite news|publisher = Good Morning America | accessdate =March 16, 2015| url= http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/story?id=126357 |title= Ron Hazelton House Tour |date= January 6, 2006}}</ref> * [[Second Church in Newton]], Newton, Massachusetts<ref>{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref> *[[Twin Oaks (Washington, D.C.)|Twin Oaks]], Washington, D.C. (Allen & Collens), the home of [[Gardiner Greene Hubbard]], founder of [[Bell Telephone Company]] and the [[National Geographic Society]] * [[Union Theological Seminary (New York)|Union Theological Seminary]], W. 120th St. and Broadway, New York, New York (Allen & Collens)<ref name=nris/> * [[United Congregational Church (Bridgeport, Connecticut)|United Congregational Church]], 877 Park Ave. [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]] (Allen & Collens)<ref name=nris/><ref name="nrhpinv3_UCC">{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=84000822}} |title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: United Congregational Church |date=May 1983 |author=Kate Ohno and John Herzan |publisher=National Park Service}} and {{NRHP url|id=84000822|title=''Accompanying 5 photos, from 1983''|photos=y}}</ref> * [[United States Post Office (Canandaigua, New York)|US Post Office]], 28 N. Main St., Canandaigua, New York (Allen & Collens)<ref name=nris/> * [[William Oxley Thompson Memorial Library]], [[Ohio State University]], [[Columbus, Ohio]] (Allen & Collens)<ref name="ksa">{{cite web|url=https://ksamedia.osu.edu/work/48486|title=William Oxley Thompson Memorial Library|website=Austin E. Knowlton School of Architecture Digital Library|publisher=The Ohio State University|access-date=October 6, 2016}}</ref>
