[[Image:Clach a' Mheirlich.JPG|thumb|Picture of the stone, taken in July 2006.]] The '''Clach a' Mheirlich''' (literally, the "Thief's stone") or '''Rosskeen Stone''' is a [[standing stone]] in a field near [[Rosskeen]], [[Easter Ross]], [[Scotland]].
The stone itself is [[Bronze Age]] in origin, but has on it three incised Pictish-style symbols barely visible on the surface of the stone, making it a Class I [[Pictish stones|Pictish symbol stone]].
==References== * MacNamara, Ellen, ''The Pictish Stones of Easter Ross'', (Tain, 2003) * Scott, Douglas, ''The Stones of the Pictish Peninsulas'', (Hilton Trust, 2004)
